  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Based on our explorations, we recommend four methods for critical, ethical, and empowering design of AI/ML systems: (1) Miracle method (Iivari et al. 2024a) invited children to imagine a bullying-free futures, revealing rich insights into the oppressive status quo but also desirable futures to design for (Iivari et al. 2024a).",
    "; (2) Critical reflection on underlying assumptions, values and best-and worst-case consequences of design invited children to critically consider their own role and responsibility as designers shaping the future, and the consequences of AI/ML systems on people's lives (Iivari et al. 2024b); (3) Theatre of the Oppressed method (Iivari et al. 2024a) invited children to discuss their designs within their school community and to mobilize the community for collective action taking against bullying, fostering empathy towards and the necessity to work on behalf of the bullying victims.",
    "; and (4) Design activism (Iivari et al. 2024a), finally, invited children to engage their school community through activism campaigns and anti-bullying designs to mobilize everyone to take action against this vicious problem, making visible personal responsibility to do so.",
    "Criticality in the sense of critique and radical change picture in these methods, as well as reflections on right and wrong, desirable and undesirable futures -including with AI/ML systems.",
    "Relational and motivational empowerment of child-designers and bullying victims picture strong in the design, but also collective empowerment of entire school communities."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Based on our explorations, we recommend four methods for critical, ethical, and empowering design of AI/ML systems: (1) Miracle method (Iivari et al. 2024a) invited children to imagine a bullying-free futures, revealing rich insights into the oppressive status quo but also desirable futures to design for (Iivari et al. 2024a).",
    "; (2) Critical reflection on underlying assumptions, values and best-and worst-case consequences of design invited children to critically consider their own role and responsibility as designers shaping the future, and the consequences of AI/ML systems on people's lives (Iivari et al. 2024b); (3) Theatre of the Oppressed method (Iivari et al. 2024a) invited children to discuss their designs within their school community and to mobilize the community for collective action taking against bullying, fostering empathy towards and the necessity to work on behalf of the bullying victims.",
    "; and (4) Design activism (Iivari et al. 2024a), finally, invited children to engage their school community through activism campaigns and anti-bullying designs to mobilize everyone to take action against this vicious problem, making visible personal responsibility to do so."
